    "moralLesson": "This hadith (Sahih Muslim) presents a transformative spiritual psychology: the believer's entire life (حَيَاةُ الْمُؤْمِنِ) is characterized as good (خَيْرٌ كُلُّهَا) regardless of external circumstances. The secret lies in the believer's response, not the event itself. The binary framework creates a complete worldview: all experiences fall into two categories (good or hardship), and for each there's an appropriate response (gratitude or patience), and both responses earn divine reward (الثَّوَاب). This eliminates the category of 'meaningless suffering'—every trial becomes an opportunity for spiritual gain through patience, just as every blessing becomes an opportunity through gratitude. The parallel structure (عِنْدَمَا...يَشْكُرُ // عِنْدَمَا...يَصْبِرُ) reinforces the symmetry. The concluding phrase 'this is the believer's way' (هَذَا طَرِيقُ الْمُؤْمِنِ) makes this attitude definitional—not optional but constitutive of faith itself.",
